  "response_text": "An old-fashioned dark book fills the view, its cover lettered in ornate gold script, “The Legend of Spryte.” A small hand turns the cover, revealing painted storybook pages. The first illustration is a moody landscape with rolling green hills, a winding path, dark trees overhead, and a tiny yellow-clad figure near the lower left. The page changes into a brightly colored toy-store aisle, drawn like a fantasy illustration, with shelves packed on both sides and toys displayed along the floor. White text briefly appears along the bottom: “Copyright Hills Department Stores, Inc.”\n\nThe illustrated scene shifts into a cozy workshop-like room. A small, elderly-looking elf or gnome character with a long white beard, rosy cheeks, round glasses, and a purple-and-yellow cap sits among toys and gadgets. A ladder climbs the back wall, a glowing lamp sits on a table, and a clock and tools decorate the warm, cluttered room. At the bottom, bold yellow words build into the slogan, “Hills Is Where The Toys Are!” The character raises his arm as if presenting the magical toy-filled world.\n\nThe image blends into a close view of the same bearded character in a real toy display area. He has pale skin, curly white hair, a full white beard, and a soft purple cap with yellow and red sections. His eyes glance upward and sideways with a playful, alert expression. As more of him is visible, he is wearing a light shirt, dark overalls, and a large blue backpack-style toy pack strapped to his back. Shelves and boxes of toys surround him.\n\nHe turns beside stacks of “The Real Ghostbusters” toy boxes and holds a blue-and-yellow Ghostbusters-style blaster with a long yellow tube projecting forward. The blue backpack on his back has colorful stickers and molded details, like a proton pack. He aims the yellow tube toward a display of Ghostbusters products. The round “The Real Ghostbusters” logo, with the white ghost crossed out by a red slash, appears large on the left among the